    <h2>Top Planetary Mixer Brands in India</h2>

    <h3>Hobart (USA) — Premium Grade</h3>
    <p>Hobart is the gold standard for planetary mixers worldwide. Exceptionally durable, precise, and backed by a global service network. Used in 5-star hotels, large restaurant chains, and professional bakeries. The Hobart Legacy HL series is the benchmark. However, Hobart mixers are significantly more expensive than alternatives.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Price in India: ₹1,20,000 – ₹8,00,000</li>
      <li>Pros: Exceptional durability, best-in-class mixing performance, global service</li>
      <li>Cons: Expensive; spare parts can take time to source in smaller cities</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Sinmag (Taiwan) — Best Mid-Range</h3>
    <p>Sinmag makes highly regarded planetary mixers used widely in Indian bakeries and restaurants. Good build quality, reliable performance, and a growing service network in India. Popular models: SM-10 (10L), SM-20 (20L), SM-30 (30L).</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Price in India: ₹55,000 – ₹2,50,000</li>
      <li>Pros: Good quality for price, reliable, decent Indian service network</li>
      <li>Cons: Not as robust as Hobart over very long periods of intensive use</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Ekon / Genius (India) — Budget Options</h3>
    <p>Indian-made planetary mixers offer the lowest prices. Quality has improved significantly in recent years. For home bakers and very small commercial operations, they're a reasonable option. For intensive commercial use, we recommend a Taiwanese or European brand.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Price in India: ₹18,000 – ₹1,00,000</li>
      <li>Pros: Affordable, locally made, parts available</li>
      <li>Cons: Variable quality, shorter lifespan under heavy commercial use</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Dito Sama (Italy) — Mid-to-Premium</h3>
    <p>Italian-made mixers with good build quality and performance. The TC series is popular among professional bakeries in India. A step below Hobart in price with very good quality.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Price in India: ₹80,000 – ₹3,50,000</li>
      <li>Pros: Italian quality, good performance, better value than Hobart</li>
      <li>Cons: Smaller service network in India</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to Choose the Right Capacity Planetary Mixer</h2>
    <p>The most common mistake when buying a planetary mixer is getting one that's too small for your production needs. Here's a practical sizing guide:</p>

    <h3>Batch Size Capacity</h3>
    <p>A planetary mixer bowl should never be filled more than 60–70% of its rated capacity for optimal mixing. So a 10-litre mixer effectively handles about 6–7 litres of batter or dough per batch.</p>

    <h3>Flour Capacity Guidelines (per batch)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>5 litre mixer:</strong> Up to 1.5 kg flour (for dough); 800g flour for cake batter</li>
      <li><strong>10 litre mixer:</strong> Up to 3 kg flour (for dough); 1.5 kg flour for cake batter</li>
      <li><strong>20 litre mixer:</strong> Up to 6 kg flour; 3 kg for cake batter</li>
      <li><strong>30 litre mixer:</strong> Up to 9 kg flour; 4.5 kg for cake batter</li>
      <li><strong>40 litre mixer:</strong> Up to 12 kg flour; 6 kg for cake batter</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Planetary Mixer vs Spiral Mixer: Which Do You Need?</h2>
    <p>If you bake significant quantities of bread or pizza dough, read our detailed comparison: <a href="/blog/planetary-vs-spiral-mixer">Planetary Mixer vs Spiral Mixer: Complete Comparison</a>.</p>
    <p>In brief: planetary mixers are better for cakes, pastries, and versatility. Spiral mixers are better for high-volume bread and pizza dough production. Many bakeries have both.</p>

