    <h2>What to Look for When Buying a Planetary Mixer</h2>
    <p><strong>Motor power:</strong> More HP = more ability to handle stiff doughs without overheating. For a 10-litre mixer, look for at least 0.75 HP. Don't trust the nameplate alone — ask about continuous-duty rating.</p>
    <p><strong>Speed settings:</strong> Professional planetary mixers have at least 3 speeds (some have 5 or variable speed). More speed options give you more control over the final texture.</p>
    <p><strong>Bowl lift vs head tilt:</strong> Large commercial mixers (20L+) use bowl-lift design (more stable). Smaller mixers (up to 15L) often use head-tilt design (easier to remove bowl and attachments).</p>
    <p><strong>Safety guard:</strong> A bowl guard that stops the mixer if opened is essential for commercial kitchens. This is a FSSAI safety requirement for commercial food production equipment.</p>
    <p><strong>Overload protection:</strong> The mixer should automatically cut out if overloaded rather than burning out the motor. Essential for longevity.</p>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which planetary mixer is best for a bakery in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For a small-medium bakery in India, the Sinmag 10-litre or 20-litre planetary mixer offers the best balance of quality and price (₹55,000 – ₹1,60,000). For a larger operation willing to invest more, Hobart is the premium choice. For very tight budgets, Indian-made mixers from Genius or Ekon are acceptable starting points.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What size planetary mixer do I need for my bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Size your mixer based on your largest single batch requirement. A home-to-small commercial baker needs a 5–7 litre mixer. A small bakery doing 50–150 items/day needs 10–15 litres. A medium bakery doing 200–500 items/day needs 20–30 litres. A large commercial operation needs 40–60 litres.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can a planetary mixer mix bread dough? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes, with the dough hook attachment. However, planetary mixers are less efficient than spiral mixers for bread dough because the mixing action generates more heat and doesn't develop gluten as gently. For small quantities of bread dough (under 3 kg of flour at a time), a planetary mixer is fine. For larger quantities or a bread-focused bakery, a spiral mixer is better. Read: <a href="/blog/planetary-vs-spiral-mixer">Planetary vs Spiral Mixer</a>.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How long does a commercial planetary mixer last? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A well-maintained commercial planetary mixer should last 10–20 years. Hobart mixers are famous for lasting 30+ years with proper maintenance. Indian-made mixers typically last 5–10 years under commercial use. Key maintenance tasks: regular oil changes in the gearbox, keeping attachments clean, not overloading the bowl, and annual professional servicing.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the difference between a 5-speed and a 3-speed planetary mixer? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A 5-speed mixer gives more precise control over mixing intensity and is better for delicate mixing tasks like mousses and merigue. A 3-speed mixer (slow, medium, fast) is adequate for most bakery applications. Unless you're doing highly technical pastry work, the difference in practical terms is minimal. Most Indian bakeries are perfectly well-served by a 3-speed mixer.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

